'''Carl Joachim Hambro''' (7 June 1914 <U+2013> 19 February 1985) was a Norwegian novelist, journalist, essayist, translator and [[Romance studies|Romance philologist]]. The son of the [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative]] politician [[C. J. Hambro]], he embarked on a [[philological]] career, graduating in 1939. During the [[Second World War]] he taught at [[Oslo Commerce School]] and the Norwegian College in Uppsala. After the war, he taught [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] at [[University of Paris-Sorbonne|Sorbonne]], whilst also working as Paris correspondent for the [[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] and a few Norwegian daily newspapers.

Born into a well-read and educated family, Hambro developed a penchant for [[French literature]], marking an incongruity to the literary taste of his parents<U+2014>they had been readers of [[English literature]] in the Anglo-American tradition. Making his debut in 1960 with the satirical novel ''De frafalnes klubb'', Hambro published trilogies and other novels for the next two decades. He had a keen interest in [[linguistics]]; in the 1969 book ''Ting, tanke, tale'' he problematized [[Philosophy of language|linguistic questions]] in a popular scientific way. A translator of French literature, he chaired the [[Norwegian Association of Literary Translators]] in the early 1960s.

==Personal life==
Hambro was born to the [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative]] [[president of the Storting|President of the Parliament]] [[C. J. Hambro|Carl Joachim Hambro]] (1885<U+2013>1964) and his first wife Gudrun "Dudu" Grieg (1881<U+2013>1943) in [[Oslo|Kristiania]] (now Oslo).<ref name=filolog>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Hambro, Carl Joachim|encyclopedia=Norges filologer og realister|editor1-first=Helga Sverdrup|editor1-last=Ekrheim|editor2-first=Olav|editor2-last=Ekrheim|editor3-first=H<U+00E5>kon|editor3-last=Nor<U+00E5>s|publisher=Dreyer|location=Stavanger|year=1950|edition=2nd|oclc=559900793|page=281|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Carl Joachim Hambro <U+2013> norsk forfatter og filolog|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor-first=Anne Marit|editor-last=Godal|editor-link=Anne Marit Godal|url=http://www.snl.no/Carl_Joachim_Hambro/norsk_forfatter_og_filolog|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2 July 2012}}</ref> He was a brother of [[Edvard Hambro|Edvard]], [[Cato Hambro|Cato]] and [[Johan Hambro]].<ref name=snl2>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Hambro|encyclopedia=Store norske leksikon|editor-first=Anne Marit|editor-last=Godal|url=http://www.snl.no/Hambro|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2 July 2012}}</ref> In 1946, following his father's marriage to [[Gyda Christensen]], he became her stepson.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2001|title=C J Hambro|encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Paul|last=Thyness|authorlink=Paul Thyness|editor-first=Knut|editor-last=Helle|editor-link=Knut Helle|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|volume=4|edition=2nd|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/C_J_Hambro/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Hambro, Carl Joachim|encyclopedia=Norges filologer og realister|editor1-first=Helga Sverdrup|editor1-last=Ekrheim|editor2-first=Olav|editor2-last=Ekrheim|editor3-first=H<U+00E5>kon|editor3-last=Nor<U+00E5>s|publisher=Dreyer|location=Stavanger|year=1950|edition=2nd|oclc=559900793|page=280|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Carl Joachim Hambro was also a paternal grandson of [[Edvard Isak Hambro (educator)|Edvard Isak Hambro]] and [[Nicoline Hambro|Nicoline Christine Harbitz]], and nephew of [[Elise Hambro]].<ref name=snl2/><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Hambro, Elise|encyclopedia=Norges filologer og realister|editor1-first=Helga Sverdrup|editor1-last=Ekrheim|editor2-first=Olav|editor2-last=Ekrheim|editor3-first=H<U+00E5>kon|editor3-last=Nor<U+00E5>s|publisher=Dreyer|location=Stavanger|year=1950|edition=2nd|oclc=559900793|page=281|language=Norwegian}}</ref>

On 15 July 1939, Hambro married Wenche Rynning Koren (born 1916);<ref name=filolog/> the marriage produced three children, among them [[Ellen Hambro]], who would later become director of Norway's [[Norwegian Climate and Pollution Agency|Climate and Pollution Agency]].<ref>{{cite news|title=&#91;Death announcement&#93;|newspaper=[[Aftenposten]]|date=20 February 1985|page=11|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Ellen Hambro|url=http://snl.no/Ellen_Hambro|encyclopedia=Store norske leksikon|editor-first=Anne Marit|editor-last=Godal|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2 July 2012}}</ref> He was also an uncle of [[Christian Hambro]].<ref name=snl2/> He died on 20 February 1985<ref name=obit/> and was buried in [[Grefsen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disnorge.no/gravminner/index.php?language=engelsk|title=Cemeteries in Norway|publisher=DIS-Norge|accessdate=1 April 2012}}</ref>

==Career==
Hambro graduated with a [[cand.philol.]] degree in 1939, having [[matriculation|matriculated]] seven years previously. At the outbreak of war, he was employed at the [[Oslo Commerce School]], where he lectured until 1943. After a short spell at the Norwegian College in Uppsala, he returned to Oslo, teaching at the Commerce School until 1946. Concurrently with his teaching, he lectured in [[French literature]] at the [[Norwegian College of Libraries and Information|Norwegian Library College]] (1940<U+2013>1941 and 1945<U+2013>1946).<ref name=filolog/> After that, he travelled to Paris, teaching Norwegian at Sorbonne until 1949.<ref name=snl/> He also worked as a correspondent for the Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation (1946<U+2013>1948), ''[[Dagbladet]]'' (1946<U+2013>1948), ''[[Verdens Gang]]'' (1948<U+2013>1949) and ''[[Arbeiderbladet]]'' (1949<U+2013>1951).<ref name=snl/><ref>{{cite book|title=Pressefolk. Biografiske opplysninger om Norsk Presseforbunds medlemmer|editor-last=Solheim|editor-first=John|year=1950|publisher=[[Norwegian Press Association]]|edition=3rd|location=Oslo|oclc=62624370|language=Norwegian|page=41}}</ref> In the next decade he would act as cultural counsellor at the Norwegian embassy in London; employed in 1952, he acted in that position for seven years, whereupon he was hired as a lecturer in Oslo.<ref name=snl/>

His debut novel was the satirical ''De frafalnes klubb'', published in 1960. He followed with a trilogy, comprising the novels ''Frels oss fra det gode'' (1963), ''Utfor stryket'' (1964) and ''Vi vil oss en dr<U+00F8>m'' (1966), which delineate the adolescence of a young man in the [[West End of Oslo]]. In 1966 he delivered a vehement critique of the Norwegian education system in the pamphlet ''Er gymnasiaster mennesker?''. He continued with ''Bj<U+00F8>rnen sover'' in 1967, a novel of a marriage, before releasing his [[semantic]] and [[psycholinguistics|psycholinguistic]] study ''Ting, tanke, tale'' in 1969<ref name=snl/><U+2014>the journalist Iver Tore Svenning recognizes this work as one of the very few successful attempts at a popular scientific treatment of [[structural linguistics]].<ref name=70ar/> His last novels were ''N<U+00F8>dhavn'' and ''Lekkasje'', released in 1971 and 1974.<ref name=snl/><ref name=obit>{{cite news|date=20 February 1985|author=Jor, Finn|authorlink=Finn Jor|work=[[Aftenposten]]|language=Norwegian|title=Carl Hambro (obituary)|page=11}}</ref>

He nevertheless continued his writings, albeit in the non-fiction genre: in the 1970s he penned numerous articles on political and literary topics for Norwegian newspapers and periodicals.<ref name=snl/> His obituarist [[Finn Jor]] describes him as a man fond of debate with a keen interest in societal issues, yet who was no front person in public dialogue, not possessing the eloquence of his father C. J. Hambro.<ref name=obit/> In the latter part of his life he wrote books on the Norwegian authors [[Jens Bj<U+00F8>rneboe]] and [[Arnulf <U+00D8>verland]].<ref name=snl/> He was active in the [[Norwegian Authors' Union]], becoming known as "a man of compromises" after having calmed a [[Norwegian language conflict|linguistic debate]] in the union.<ref name=70ar>{{cite news|date=7 June 1984|author=Svenning, Iver Tore|work=[[Aftenposten]]|language=Norwegian|title=Carl Hambro 70 <U+00E5>r: Den allsidige forfatter|page=14}}</ref>

A renowned translator of French prose, Hambro chaired the [[Norwegian Association of Literary Translators]] from 1961 to 1965;<ref name=snl/> he was awarded the [[Bastian Prize]] for translation in 1963.<ref name=snl-bastian>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Bastianprisen|encyclopedia=Store norske leksikon|editor-first=Anne Marit|editor-last=Godal|url=http://www.snl.no/Bastianprisen|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2 July 2012}}</ref>

